3b4d8fdd-0f7a-4586-9f12-9c7080fd2f79.2b321434-2eb2-48d3-b3a5-b281e455e8ac.description=
Opens or updates a Change Ticket in Service Now and/or runs or schedules a run of an NA script.  Will also open a Request Ticket if the device is a firewall.

This flow is used for one of five operations related to NA Change Requests.  The inputs will be marked with what is required for each operation.

The five operations are (in order of precedence)\:

CANCEL- Cancel a scheduled change.
CONFIRM - Confirm a change as "Successful" or "Unsuccessful".
BACKOUT - Backout a change that's already run (within 24 hours).
RUNNOW - Run a script at the next earliest possible time.
SCHEDULE - Schedule the script to run at a specified time (default if no other operation is triggered)

Inputs\:
phost - Required for RUNNOW and SCHEDULE - Name of the device where the script will run
phostType -  Required for RUNNOW and SCHEDULE - Type of device for phost (valid options are Firewall, Switch, or Router)
scriptName -  Required for RUNNOW and SCHEDULE - Name of the NA script
scriptVariables -  Required for RUNNOW and SCHEDULE - Variables for the NA script
startDateTime -  Required for SCHEDULE - The date and time to run the script
company -  Required for RUNNOW and SCHEDULE - Company of submitting user from ViewPoint
requested_by -  Required for RUNNOW and SCHEDULE - Email of submitting user from ViewPoint
sys_id - Required for CANCEL, CONFIRM, and BACKOUT - The ticket's sys_id
cancelScheduledChange -  Set to 'True' to perform a CANCEL operation -  Cancels a change that has already been scheduled.
confirmChange - Set to 'True' to perform a CONFIRM operation - Confirms a change that has already run as either successful or unsuccessful.
confirmationStatus - Required for CONFIRM - The status to the change to (valid options are Successful or Unsuccessful).
backoutChange -  Set to 'True' to perform a BACKOUT operation - Backs a change out according to the Backout Plan.  Also closes the ticket, opens a new 'backout' ticket, and cancels the scheduled ticket close flow.
runNow -  Set to 'True' to perform a RUNNOW operation - Runs a script at the earliest possible time and creates a ticket for the change.

Outputs\:
sys_id - The Service Now system identifier for the change.
ticketNum - The Change Ticket number in Service Now (eg CHG\#\#\#\#)
docRequestNum - The Request Ticket number for the Document Request (eg RITM\#\#\#\#)

Responses\:
Success - The requested operation completed successfully
Failure - There was an error attempting to complete the operation
3b4d8fdd-0f7a-4586-9f12-9c7080fd2f79.319c1af7-fe3b-4fee-97b8-aea4a69e8990.description=
Offsets the current date and time by a given number of units. If locale is specified, the date and time will be in the format based on the locale. Otherwise, default locale will be used. 

Inputs\:
    units - The number of units to offset by. If this is positive, the offset goes into the future, if it is negative the offset goes into the past.
    secondsPerUnit - The number of seconds per unit. This defaults to 1 hour, thus the units is by default measured in hours.
    localeLang - The locale language for date and time string.
Examples;  en, ja, unix.
    localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ingored.

Returns\:
    The offset date/time. 

Responses\:
    success - Operation completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Notes.
    1. If you need the output to be a UNIX timestamp, use the value 'unix' for localeLang. In this case, the localeCountry input will be ignored and the result of the operation will be in UNIX format.

3b4d8fdd-0f7a-4586-9f12-9c7080fd2f79.b6b1f85f-4cfd-46b9-ac89-4aa21001e4e4.description=
This operation converts the date input value from one date/time format (specified by dateFormat) to another date/time format (specified by outFormat) using locale settings (language and country).
You can use the flow "Get Current Date and Time" to check upon the default date/time format from the Java environement.  

Inputs\:
    date - The date to parse/convert.
    dateFormat - The format of the input date.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    dateLocaleLang - The locale language for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    dateLocaleCountry - The locale country for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty or dateLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR
    outFormat - The format of the output date/time.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    outLocaleLang - The locale language for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    outLocaleCountry - The locale country for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty or outLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR

Results\:
    returnResult - The date in the new format.

Responses\:
    success - The date was converted.
    failure - The date could not be converted.

Notes\:
    1. If default locale language from the Java environement is English, the input dateFormat is empty and the input outFormat is empty, the input date should be in the format of "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the user specifies dateFormat as "dd-MM-YYYY HH\:mm\:ss", the input date should be in the format of "13-07-2006 10\:04\:08". If the input outFormat is empty, the result will be "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the input outFormat is "yyyy-MM-dd", the result will be "2006-07-13". The dateFormat for "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:078 AM" is "MMM dd, yyyy HH\:mm\:ss a".
    2. Note that the dateFormat and outFormat inputs are case sensitive. 'M' is used for months representation and 'm' for minutes.
    3. Within date and time pattern strings, unquoted letters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are interpreted as pattern letters representing the components of a date or time string. Text can be quoted using single quotes (') to avoid interpretation. "''" represents a single quote. All other characters are not interpreted; they're simply copied into the output string during formatting or matched against the input string during parsing. The following pattern letters are defined (all other characters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are reserved)\:

Letter	Date or Time Component			Presentation		Examples
G	Era designator				Text		AD
y	Year				Year		1996; 96
Y	Week year				Year		2009; 09
M	Month in year				Month		July; Jul; 07
w	Week in year				Number		27
W	Week in month				Number		2
D	Day in year				Number		189
d	Day in month				Number		10
F	Day of week in month			Number		2
E	Day name in week			Text		Tuesday; Tue
u	Day number of week (1 \= Monday, ..., 7 \= Sunday)	Number		1
a	Am/pm marker				Text		PM
H	Hour in day (0-23)			Number		0
k	Hour in day (1-24)			Number		24
K	Hour in am/pm (0-11)			Number		0
h	Hour in am/pm (1-12)			Number		12
m	Minute in hour				Number		30
s	Second in minute			Number		55
S	Millisecond				Number		978
z	Time zone				General time zone	Pacific Standard Time; PST; GMT-08\:00
Z	Time zone				RFC 822 time zone	-800
X	Time zone				ISO 8601 time zone	-08; -0800; -08\:00
Special case\:
unix	Unix timestamp			Number		1384326000

Examples for the date 2001-07-04 12\:08\:56 in U.S. Pacific Time\:

Date			DateFromat			DateLocaleLang	DateLocaleCountry
2001.07.04 AD at 12\:08\:56 PDT	yyyy.MM.dd G 'at' HH\:mm\:ss z		en		US
Wed, Jul 4, '01			EEE, MMM d, ''yy		en		US
2001-07-04T12\:08\:56.235+0700	yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSZ	en		US
2001-07-04T12\:08\:56.235-07\:00	yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX	en		US
1309781336			unix			-		-
3b4d8fdd-0f7a-4586-9f12-9c7080fd2f79.ba90f58a-de3b-4652-b1db-3806b1c82bdb.description=
This operation waits for the number of seconds specified in the "seconds" input.

Inputs\:
    seconds - The number of seconds to wait.

Results\:
    resultString – This is the primary output. It contains the "completed sleep" message if the operation completed successfully and an error message otherwise. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
